  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Local Inventory Ads (LIA)</strong> are a Google Shopping ad format that promotes products physically available in a nearby retail store. When a shopper within a configurable radius searches for a matching product, the ad shows the item's in-store price and availability with a badge reading "In store" — driving foot traffic rather than online purchases.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Ad type</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Google Shopping (local variant)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO / Paid Advertising</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Goal</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Drive in-store foot traffic</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">The problem Local Inventory Ads solve is specific: a shopper searches for a product online, sees it on Amazon, and orders it for two-day delivery — never knowing your store has it on the shelf right now, 1.2 miles away. LIA closes that gap by making your physical inventory visible in Google's shopping results before the online purchase is made.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What are Local Inventory Ads?</h2>
        <p>Local Inventory Ads sit within Google's Shopping advertising ecosystem as a format specifically designed for brick-and-mortar retailers. Unlike standard Google Shopping ads that link to a product page on your ecommerce site, LIA clicks land on a <em>local storefront</em> — either a Google-hosted version (called a Google-hosted local storefront) or a retailer-hosted version (a dedicated page on your site).</p>
        <p>The local storefront shows:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>The product image, price, and description</li>
          <li>Current in-store stock status (In stock / Limited availability / Out of stock)</li>
          <li>Store address, hours, and directions link</li>
          <li>Click-to-call button for the specific location</li>
          <li>Nearby location options if the shopper is between multiple stores</li>
        </ul>
        <p>From the shopper's perspective, they search for a product, see an ad with "In store nearby" messaging, click it, confirm the product is available at the store 0.8 miles away, and drive there. From the retailer's perspective, they just captured a high-intent buyer who was moments away from purchasing online from a competitor.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why this matters in 2026</div>
          <p>Google reports that <strong>searches for "available near me" have grown over 100% in the past two years</strong>. Shoppers increasingly expect to confirm local availability before leaving home. LIA is the direct advertising response to this behaviour — showing product availability before the purchase decision is locked in.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why Local Inventory Ads matter for retailers</h2>
        <p>Retailers with physical locations face a structural disadvantage in standard search advertising: they're competing against Amazon, Walmart, and pure-play ecommerce sites that have faster delivery and a better online purchase experience. LIA flips the competitive dynamic by highlighting the one thing online retailers can't offer — the product available right now, nearby, no delivery wait.</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Capture "buy local" demand before it converts online.</strong> A shopper searching "iPhone 15 case" at 2pm Saturday isn't necessarily committed to online purchase. An LIA showing your store has the case in stock at a store 0.7 miles away converts that search into a same-day store visit.</li>
          <li><strong>Higher in-store conversion vs website conversion.</strong> Google data shows store visits from LIA clicks convert at 25-35% — significantly higher than typical ecommerce conversion rates of 1-3%. Once a shopper is in-store, basket size also tends to be larger.</li>
          <li><strong>Compete for "near me" searches in Shopping.</strong> LIA allows your products to appear in the "nearby" filter on Google Shopping, a high-intent placement that standard Shopping campaigns cannot access.</li>
          <li><strong>Real-time inventory reduces wasted ad spend.</strong> Because LIA links to an inventory feed updated daily, shoppers only see your ad if the product is actually in stock. You stop paying for clicks that would end in a "sorry, out of stock" store visit.</li>
          <li><strong>Measurable offline conversion.</strong> Google's store visit conversions (enabled via Google Ads + Google Maps data) let you track how many LIA clicks resulted in actual store visits, making the ROI on LIA measurable.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Local Inventory Ads work — step by step</h2>
        <p>Setting up LIA requires four components connected through Google Merchant Center:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Primary product feed.</strong> The standard Merchant Center feed containing your full product catalogue — name, price, image, GTIN, description, availability at the main level.</li>
          <li><strong>Local product inventory feed.</strong> A supplementary feed that maps specific products to specific store locations with quantity on hand. Format: store_code, item_id, quantity, price (if different from online). Updated daily minimum.</li>
          <li><strong>Google Business Profile (verified).</strong> Each participating store location must have a verified GBP. The GBP provides the address, hours, and phone number that appears on the local storefront page.</li>
          <li><strong>Local storefront page.</strong> Either Google-hosted (set up within Merchant Center) or retailer-hosted (a page on your site that auto-pulls product availability for that location). Retailer-hosted performs better for SEO but requires developer setup.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>Once live, Google's algorithm matches product searches from shoppers within your configured radius (typically 20-50 miles) against your inventory feed. When a match occurs, your LIA appears in Google Search, Google Shopping, and Google Maps search results.</p>

        <h2 id="types">LIA formats — what options are available?</h2>

