        <h2 id="examples">Real Local Inventory Ads examples</h2>
        <p>Here are three retail scenarios showing LIA working in practice.</p>

        <h3>1. Electronics retailer — capturing impulse buy</h3>
        <p>A shopper's phone charger breaks on a Friday afternoon. They search "USB-C charger" on Google. A local electronics retailer's LIA appears: "USB-C 65W Charger — $24.99 · In stock at [Store Name] · 1.2 mi." The shopper clicks, confirms the product is available in stock at the store 1.2 miles away, and drives there — arriving before they could even receive Amazon's next-day delivery.</p>

        <h3>2. Auto parts store — need-it-now purchase</h3>
        <p>A car owner needs a specific air filter for a weekend DIY oil change. They search "Fram PH3614 oil filter" on Google Shopping. The auto parts store's LIA shows "In store — aisle 7" with the store 0.9 miles away. Purchase conversion rate for this type of need-it-now auto part query reaches 40%+ in-store.</p>

        <h3>3. Apparel brand — reducing showrooming</h3>
        <p>A shopper sees a jacket online and wants to try it on before buying. They search for the jacket model on Google Shopping, filtering by "Available nearby." The brand's LIA shows the item available in two sizes at a store 3 miles away. The shopper visits, tries both sizes, and purchases in-store — plus adds two accessories the LIA didn't advertise.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Local Inventory Ads vs standard Google Shopping — which to use</h2>
        <p>Most retailers with physical locations should run both simultaneously, not choose one over the other. They target different conversion paths.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use Local Inventory Ads when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You have physical store locations</li>
              <li>Products are needed immediately (auto parts, chargers, medicine)</li>
              <li>Your store has a competitive advantage over online price</li>
              <li>Products have high touch/try-on value (apparel, shoes, furniture)</li>
              <li>You want to measure offline conversions</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use standard Shopping ads when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Your primary sales channel is ecommerce</li>
              <li>Products are shipped nationwide</li>
              <li>No physical store inventory to map</li>
              <li>Products have high online research value</li>
              <li>You're targeting national rather than local demand</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for Local Inventory Ads</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Keep your inventory feed updated at least daily.</strong> Stale inventory data is the number-one LIA failure mode. A shopper who drives to your store and finds the product out of stock leaves a negative review. Automate your feed update to sync with your POS system overnight.</li>
          <li><strong>Start with your top 20% highest-velocity products.</strong> Not every SKU needs LIA. Identify the products with the highest local search volume and run LIA on those first. Expand as you validate the feed setup and conversion tracking.</li>
          <li><strong>Use retailer-hosted storefronts where possible.</strong> Google-hosted storefronts are faster to implement but provide no SEO benefit and limited customisation. Retailer-hosted storefronts can be indexed, allow custom branding, and support remarketing pixels.</li>
          <li><strong>Enable store visit conversions in Google Ads.</strong> Without conversion tracking, you're bidding blind. Store visit conversions (reported when a user who clicked your LIA visits your store within 30 days) are the primary measurement mechanism for LIA ROI.</li>
          <li><strong>Bid differently for LIA vs standard Shopping.</strong> LIA clicks convert in-store at higher rates than online clicks. Adjust your ROAS targets to account for the higher-value in-store basket. Many retailers bid 20-30% higher on LIA placements than standard Shopping.</li>
          <li><strong>Verify all GBP listings are accurate and active.</strong> LIA pulls store address, hours, and phone from your GBP. Wrong hours in GBP mean shoppers arrive at a closed store. Audit every location's GBP before launching LIA.</li>
          <li><strong>Test "pickup today" messaging where eligible.</strong> Ads featuring "Available for pickup today" or "Pick up in 2 hours" messaging generate significantly higher CTR than standard "In store" labels, particularly in competitive categories.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — ignoring feed quality</div>
          <p>LIA performance is entirely dependent on feed quality. Missing GTINs, mismatched product titles between primary and inventory feeds, incorrect store codes, or prices that don't match in-store prices all cause Google to suppress your ads. Before launching, audit both feeds for: GTIN coverage (minimum 90%), title consistency, price accuracy, and store code alignment with your GBP locations.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common Local Inventory Ads mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Not mapping every store location.</strong> If you have 8 locations but only 3 are in your inventory feed, shoppers near the other 5 see no LIA. Map every location from day one.</li>
          <li><strong>Setting too-large a radius.</strong> A 50-mile radius means shoppers 45 miles away see your "nearby" ad and won't visit. Tighten to 20 miles maximum for urban markets, 30-40 miles for suburban or rural stores.</li>
          <li><strong>Running LIA without conversion tracking.</strong> Without store visit conversion data, you cannot optimise bids, identify underperforming locations, or prove ROI to stakeholders.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring mobile optimisation for local storefronts.</strong> Over 75% of LIA clicks come from mobile devices. Retailer-hosted storefronts must load in under 3 seconds on mobile and have a clear "Get directions" CTA above the fold.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating LIA as set-and-forget.</strong> Inventory changes, seasonal product mix, store hours updates, and pricing changes all require feed and GBP updates. Assign a weekly maintenance schedule to your LIA setup.</li>
        </ul>

